        {
            "id": "6e5c922f51d64dc4ab792",
            "questionText": "During a long summer drive, the air inside your car tire, which is a gas, initially has a pressure of $!$200\\,\\text{kPa}$!$ at a temperature of $!$20^\\circ\\text{C}$!$. As the drive continues, the tire's temperature rises to $!$50^\\circ\\text{C}$!$ while the volume remains constant. Calculate the new pressure (in $!$\\text{kPa}$!$) of the air inside the tire using Gay-Lussac's Law, ensuring all temperatures are converted to Kelvin.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "eeab39d310e24fb6847ab",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct temperature conversion formula from Celsius to Kelvin. Which of the following formulas correctly converts a temperature $!$\\theta$!$ in Celsius to Kelvin?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\theta + 273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\theta - 273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\theta \\times 273$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "1069a6aa9c024d489850b",
                    "stepText": "Now, convert the initial temperature of $!$20^\\circ\\text{C}$!$ to Kelvin using the formula you identified.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "293"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "8ba5ca26787c491abdea2",
                    "stepText": "Next, convert the final temperature of $!$50^\\circ\\text{C}$!$ to Kelvin using the same conversion formula.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "323"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "K",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f4186011-be31-4acd-ae74-62cc65bae364"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "e2df52ba5fa94e04b47b1",
                    "stepText": "Great, now identify the correct expression of Gay-Lussac's Law which relates pressure and temperature when the volume is constant. Which of the following options correctly represents Gay-Lussac's Law?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\frac{p}{T} = \\text{constant}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p \\times T = \\text{constant}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p - T = \\text{constant}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6b5705c324984d889bcd2",
                    "stepText": "Now, rearrange Gay-Lussac's Law to solve for the new pressure $!$p_2$!$ in terms of the initial pressure and temperatures. Which of the following rearranged formulas is correct?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2adfd026-0718-4727-9c26-9492969f7ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2 = p_1 \\times \\frac{T_2}{T_1}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2 = p_1 \\times \\frac{T_1}{T_2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p_2 = p_1 + (T_2 - T_1)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "7bdb10a92cf7406f88df3",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the expression you identified to calculate the new pressure $!$p_2$!$ by substituting the values: $!$p_1 = 200\\,\\text{kPa}$!$, $!$T_1 = 293\\,K$!$, and $!$T_2 = 323\\,K$!$. What is the new pressure?",
